To get the title from a URL in Google Sheets based on the URL column, you can use custom JavaScript functions in Google Apps Script. Here's a step-by-step guide to achieve this:

1. Create a new standalone script in Google Apps Script:
a. Go to <https://docs.google.com/script/u/0/>
b. Click "+" to create a new script, and save it with an appropriate name (e.g., "UrlTitleExtractor").
2. Add the following JavaScript function to fetch the title from the URL:
```javascript
function getTitleFromUrl(url) {
  var response = UrlFetchApp.fetch(url);
  var headers = response.getHeaders();
  var link = headers.get('Link');
  if (link) {
    var linkElements = link.split(',');
    for (var i = 0; i < linkElements.length; i++) {
      var l = linkElements[i];
      var linkTitlePosition = l.search('title');
      if (linkTitlePosition != -1) {
        var titleStartPosition = link.indexOf('>') + 1;
        var titleEndPosition = link.indexOf('<', titleStartPosition);
        if (titleEndPosition == -1) {
          titleEndPosition = link.length;
        }
        return link.substring(titleStartPosition, titleEndPosition);
      }
    }
  }
  return undefined;
}
```
1. Save your code and run the function to verify it works.
2. Go to your Google Sheets document and select the columns where you want to use the custom function. For example, if your URLs are in column A, place your cursor in the cell in column B where you want the title to appear.
