It seems there might be a problem with the logic surrounding updating classes and titles when clicking on a star. One potential issue is the conditions for updating the titles and classes when the star clicked is the same as the current rating.

Considering this part of the code in the click event listener for the stars:

```javascript
btn.addEventListener('click', event => {
  if (btn.title !== "Unset") {
    console.log('click: (btn.title !== "Unset"): btn.title : ' + btn.title);
    updateSceneRating(sceneId, btn.title);
  } else {
    console.log('click btn: (btn.title !== "Unset") else : btn.title : ' + btn.title);
    updateTitles("0");
    updateClasses(0);
    updateSceneRating(sceneId, null);
  }
});
```

If the clicked star has the same rating as the current rating, it should unset the rating (set it to null). But the current condition checks if the title is not equal to "Unset" and updates the rating. If the title is "Unset", it sets the titles, classes, and rating to 0.

I suggest updating the conditions as follows:

```javascript
btn.addEventListener('click', event => {
  if (btn.title !== "Unset" && btn.title != currentRating) {
    console.log('click: (btn.title !== "Unset" && btn.title != currentRating): btn.title : ' + btn.title);
    updateSceneRating(sceneId, btn.title);
  } else {
    console.log('click btn: (btn.title == "Unset" || btn.title == currentRating) : btn.title : ' + btn.title);
    updateTitles("Unset");
    updateClasses(0);
    updateSceneRating(sceneId, null);
  }
});
```

This condition checks if the title is not equal to "Unset" and also not equal to the current rating. If so, it updates the rating. If the title is "Unset" or equal to the current rating, it unsets the rating. This should achieve the intended functionality of toggling the rating when clicking on the same star again.

To create a list of review items in C#, you can define a class for the review item with the required properties and then create a list of that class. Here's an example:

1. First, create a class called `ReviewItem` with the properties `UserName`, `Score`, and `DateCreated`:

```csharp
public class ReviewItem
{
    public string UserName { get; set; }
    public int Score { get; set; }
    public DateTime DateCreated { get; set; }

    public ReviewItem(string userName, int score, DateTime dateCreated)
    {
        UserName = userName;
        Score = score;
        DateCreated = dateCreated;
    }
}
```

2. Now create a list of `ReviewItem` objects:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // Create a list of review items
        List<ReviewItem> reviewItems = new List<ReviewItem>
        {
            new ReviewItem("User1", 5, DateTime.Now.AddDays(-3)),
            new ReviewItem("User2", 4, DateTime.Now.AddDays(-2)),
            new ReviewItem("User3", 3, DateTime.Now.AddDays(-1)),
            new ReviewItem("User4", 2, DateTime.Today)
        };

        // Display the review items
        foreach (var review in reviewItems)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"UserName: {review.UserName}, Score: {review.Score}, DateCreated: {review.DateCreated.ToShortDateString()}");
        }
    }
}
```

When you run the program, it will display the review items with the usernames, scores, and dates created.

Here's an example using a generic exception handling middleware in ASP.NET Core to return the appropriate status code for exceptions:

1. First, create a new class called `ExceptionMiddleware` to handle exceptions:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Net;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http;

public class ExceptionMiddleware
{
    private readonly RequestDelegate _next;

    public ExceptionMiddleware(RequestDelegate next)
    {
        _next = next;
    }

    public async Task InvokeAsync(HttpContext httpContext)
    {
        try
        {
            await _next(httpContext);
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            await HandleExceptionAsync(httpContext, ex);
        }
    }

    private static Task HandleExceptionAsync(HttpContext context, Exception exception)
    {
        context.Response.ContentType = "application/json";
        context.Response.StatusCode = (int)GetErrorCode(exception);

        return context.Response.WriteAsync(new
        {
            StatusCode = context.Response.StatusCode,
            ErrorMessage = exception.Message
        }.ToString());
    }

    private static HttpStatusCode GetErrorCode(Exception exception)
    {
        switch (exception)
        {
            case ArgumentNullException _:
            case ArgumentOutOfRangeException _:
                return HttpStatusCode.BadRequest;

            case InvalidOperationException _:
                return HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError;

            default:
                return HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError;
        }
    }
}
```

2. In the `Startup.cs` file, add the new middleware to the pipeline inside the `Configure` method:

```csharp
public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app)
{
    //...
    app.UseMiddleware<ExceptionMiddleware>();
    //...
}
```

This approach will implement a generic error handling middleware that catches any unhandled exceptions during the request processing and returns an appropriate status code based on the type of exception. In the example above, it handles `ArgumentNullException`, `ArgumentOutOfRangeException`, and `InvalidOperationException` with corresponding status codes. You can easily extend this middleware to handle other custom exceptions and return different status codes as needed.

